    slug: "fath-ul-majeed-arabic",
    description: `Fath ul Majeed is an Arabic-language commentary on the renowned theological treatise Kitab at-Tawheed by Shaykh Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab, one of the most influential works on Islamic monotheism in the modern era. The original Kitab at-Tawheed is a foundational text that systematically presents the Islamic concept of God's oneness by drawing exclusively from the Quran, authentic hadith, and statements of the early generations of Muslims (Salaf). Fath ul Majeed serves as a detailed explanatory commentary that unpacks the sometimes dense and concise statements of the original text, providing readers with the historical context, linguistic analysis, and scholarly consensus needed to fully understand each chapter and principle presented by Shaykh Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab. The commentary draws upon the works of classical scholars including Ibn Taymiyyah, Ibn al-Qayyim, and other authorities in the field of aqeedah to provide a comprehensive and well-sourced explanation of each point.

The book is organized to follow the structure of Kitab at-Tawheed chapter by chapter, covering topics that include the obligation of tauheed, the categories of shirk (associating partners with Allah), the proper understanding of Allah's names and attributes, the prohibition of intermediary worship, the ruling on seeking help from other than Allah, the status of graves and shrines in Islamic practice, and the distinction between major and minor shirk. Each chapter begins with the relevant Quranic verses and hadith cited in the original text, followed by the commentary that explains the textual evidence, clarifies difficult vocabulary, provides historical background on the situations that prompted particular revelations or prophetic statements, and addresses common misconceptions and arguments raised by those who oppose the strict monotheistic position of orthodox Islam. The commentator is careful to distinguish between acts that constitute actual shirk and acts that are merely discouraged or culturally problematic, maintaining scholarly precision throughout.

Fath ul Majeed is written entirely in Arabic, making it accessible to students and scholars who have attained proficiency in classical Arabic and who are pursuing advanced studies in Islamic theology and creed. The work is widely used in Islamic universities and seminaries across the Arab world, particularly in Saudi Arabia, where it forms part of the curriculum for aqeedah courses. It is also studied by Arabic-speaking students of knowledge in other countries who are connected to the Salafi scholarly tradition. The book serves as an essential bridge between the concise original text and the reader's full comprehension, making it an indispensable companion for anyone who wishes to study Kitab at-Tawheed seriously and thoroughly. Scholars and teachers frequently reference Fath ul Majeed when preparing lessons on tauheed, and students rely on it to clarify passages that they find difficult to understand on their own. The commentary maintains the scholarly rigor and scriptural focus of the original text while adding layers of explanation that make the profound concepts of Islamic monotheism accessible to dedicated students of knowledge.`,
