    description: `Fazail e Sahabiyat Kareemat (Part 1) is the first volume of a dedicated Urdu-language work that focuses specifically on the virtues, lives, and contributions of the female companions of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) — the Sahabiyat. While many general works on the companions of the Prophet devote the majority of their attention to male figures, this series addresses the important and sometimes overlooked role that Muslim women played during the formative period of Islam. The book presents detailed biographical accounts of the most prominent women who accepted Islam during the Prophet's lifetime, highlighting their faith, their sacrifices, their intellectual contributions, their social influence, and the example they set for Muslim women in every subsequent generation.

The first volume begins with the mothers of the believers — the wives of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) — who hold a unique and elevated status among all Muslim women. Khadijah bint Khuwaylid receives extensive treatment as the first person to believe in the Prophet's message, the woman who used her wealth and social standing to support the early Muslim community, and the wife whose love and encouragement sustained the Prophet through the most difficult years of his mission in Makkah. The book presents Khadijah not merely as the Prophet's wife but as a successful businesswoman, a woman of independent means, and a person of exceptional character whose judgment the Prophet trusted completely. Aisha bint Abu Bakr is covered with equal thoroughness, emphasizing her remarkable intelligence, her vast knowledge of Islam, her role as a teacher and jurist who narrated over two thousand hadith, and her involvement in the political and social affairs of the early Muslim community. The other wives of the Prophet, including Sawdah, Hafsah, Umm Salamah, Zainab bint Jahsh, Juwayriyyah, Umm Habibah, Safiyyah, and Maymunah, each receive dedicated chapters that highlight their unique qualities and contributions.

Beyond the Prophet's household, Part 1 includes biographies of other notable female companions who played significant roles in the early Muslim community. Fatimah bint Muhammad, the Prophet's beloved daughter, is presented as a model of patience, devotion, and family life. Asma bint Abu Bakr is celebrated for her courage during the Hijrah, when she tore her garment to wrap the Prophet's provisions for the journey to Madinah, earning her the title "Dhat an-Nitaqayn" (she of the two girdles). Sumayyah bint Khayyat is honored as the first martyr in Islam, a woman who endured torture at the hands of her master rather than renounce her faith. The Urdu prose is respectful, scholarly, and engaging, presenting these women as complete personalities whose lives offer lessons in faith, courage, wisdom, and devotion. This volume is an essential resource for Muslim women seeking role models from the earliest generation of Islam, for teachers and students at Islamic educational institutions, and for anyone interested in understanding the prominent role that women played in the establishment of the Muslim community.`,
